          "body": "The psalm's center section (16:15-22) is a recitation of the Abrahamic covenant across three patriarchal generations. The verb 'remember' now shifts from Israel's obligation (16:12, 15) to YHWH's own faithfulness — He remembered His covenant when Israel was 'only a few in number, very few, and strangers' in the land (16:19). The wandering described in verse 20 — from nation to nation, from kingdom to kingdom — encompasses the entire patriarchal sojourn from Mesopotamia through Canaan to Egypt. Through all of it, God 'permitted no man to oppress them, and He reproved kings for their sakes' (16:21). The specific word used for the patriarchs — 'My anointed ones' (meshichim, 16:22) — is striking: the same root as Messiah. The patriarchs were divinely set apart and divinely protected, and their protection was a function of their anointed status before God. This section is the psalm's evidentiary core: the covenant claims of verses 15-18 are proven by the historical narrative of verses 19-22."
